{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "There are two main paradigms for obtaining safety guarantees for RL policies: verifying the policy for all possible states [7] or safeguarding the policy online [1], for both concepts, either probabilistic or hard guarantees are obtained.",
    "If the environment is dynamic, often only probabilistic guarantees can be obtained efficiently, e.g., through scenario optimization [8], [9], when verifying the policy for all states.",
    "Since we aim for hard guarantees, the safeguarding concept is better suited since it can efficiently achieve hard guarantees in dynamic environments as well [1], [2].",
    "Our approach is based on action replacement, where a post-posed safety verification identifies unsafe actions and replaces them with safe actions.",
    "Common verification methods for action verification are model checking [2], [10], theorem proving [11], reachability analysis [12]- [14] while the applicability depends on the type of state and action space."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
